@NODE "WHATISIT"

  You see, as I download tons of files from the web, there are
  often twice, trice... the same file on my harddrive in different
  directories and with different names. The fact is: I was getting
  tired of all that wasted space. I tried to find a simple solution
  to solve the problem, tested some programs that were supposed to
  do the job, but I never found something that could satisfy me.

  Thus, I made my own tool to search those twin files, and here is:

  @{B}TWIN@{UB} !

@ENDNODE

@NODE "INSTALLATION"

  Kinda easy, no need to make a script for now :)


   1) Copy twin anywhere in your path, (e.g. C:) if you want to use it in
      a shell. If you prefer to launch it like any other Workbench tool,
      just copt twin and twin.info in the drawer of your choice.

   2) Copy the catalogs drawer in your LOCALE: directory

  That's it!

   @{U}about ixemul.library@{UU}

   Previous versions of Twin needed the presence of the ixemul.library
   version 46.1+ in your LIBS:. Now I managed to get rid of this
   "dependancy" with the kind help of Jörg Strohmayer. Thus you can
   ignore the text that follows, I just let it there because it could
   help someone one day.

   You can download the lattest version of ixemul (47.2 yet) from
   ftp.ninemoons.com in /pub/geekgadgets/971125/amiga-bin

   971125 is the date the lattest release, so you may find a newer
   directory in /pub/geekgadgets (just have a look, doesn't cost much :)

@ENDNODE

@NODE "USAGE"

  How to use it?

  You can run twin from a shell or its icon

      @{"from shell " LINK "SOUSHELL"}
      @{"from icon  " LINK "ICONE"}

@ENDNODE

@NODE "SOUSHELL"


  Type twin dh0: (or any valid device) and wait =)


  @{I}NOTE: if you run Twin without further argument, the program
        starts its scan in the current directory. @{UI}


  The program scans the @{B}entire@{UB} disk (this can take time, don't
  think too quickly something's wrong) and then starts to compare
  files that could be the same, even if they are in different
  directories. It first outputs the names of files that are NULL-
  length (if any) and then tells you what are the files in double
  (if any again). There's a little display showing how many files
  were already treated.


  The differents arguments of the command line:

       @{"-noinfo    " LINK "NOINFO"}
       @{"-verbose   " LINK "VERBOSE"}
       @{"-logfile   " LINK "LOGFILE"}
       @{"-clean     " LINK "CLEAN"}
       @{"-logname   " LINK "LOGNAME"}
       @{"-requester " LINK "REQUESTER"}

@ENDNODE

@NODE "LOGNAME"

  If you use the option @{B}-l@{UB} you'll obtain the results in the
  default file ram:TWINlog. If you want to change both name and location
  of the logfile, use @{B}-ln@{UB} or @{B}-logname@{UB} followed by the
  complete pathname.

      @{I}twin dh0: -ln dh0:TWlog @{UI}

  If, for any reason, it is impossible to create the given file, then
  the output will be redirected to the screen.

@ENDNODE

@NODE "REQUESTER"

  If you don't like to type command line and long pathnames, this is
  for you! You'll be able to select the starting directory from a standard
  ASL requester. Just browse and click OK once you're in the right place.
  You can use @{B}-r@{UB} ou @{B}-requester@{UB} to activate the requester.

      @{I}twin -r @{UI}

  N.B. the -r option is "stronger" than any given path.

@ENDNODE

@NODE "NOINFO"

  If you want the program to ignore all the ".info" files, you can
  use the @{B}-n@{UB} or @{B}-noinfo@{UB} options

      e.g. @{I}twin dh0: -noinfo @{UI}

@ENDNODE

@NODE "VERBOSE"


  The @{B}-v@{UB} or @{B}-verbose@{UB} displays some extra information like
  the total number of files found on the disk, or the amount of
  memory that was allocated by the program to run. This option
  is mainly for internal purpose and doesn't help you a lot :)

      e.g. @{I}twin dh0: -v @{UI}

@ENDNODE

@NODE "LOGFILE"

  You'll quickly find out that sometimes the displays scrolls
  too fast for you to note down everything. Thus, there's the
  logging switch that allows you to get the results in the file
  ram:TWINlog. Simply use the @{B}-l@{UB} or @{B}-logfile@{UB} argument.

      @{I}twin dh0: -l@{UI}

  When the program's done, edit ram:TWINlog to get the stuff.

@ENDNODE

@NODE "CLEAN"

  Sometimes, when a transfer on the web is interrupted, it could
  be that there are some null-sized files created. Twin tells you
  each time it encounters one. If you want to, you can tell Twin
  to erase all those files with the @{B}-c@{UB} or @{B}-clean@{UB} switch.

      @{I}twin dh0: -clean@{UI}

  @{B}@{U}A T T E N T I O N@{UB}@{UU}

  This switch can be very @{B}dangerous@{UB}!!!

  It is possible that some null-sized files are used as a flag by
  the system, for example in the ENV-ARCHIVE: drawer. Erasing them
  could make your system crash, so think twice before activating
  the switch!!!!      

@ENDNODE

@NODE "ICONE"

  Launched from an icon, twin uses the TOOLTYPES to know about the options.
  TOOLTYPES have the same name their shell equivalent: you should read this
  section to know about their meaning.

   TOOLTYPE          SHELL

   @{"NOINFO      " LINK "NOINFO"}    -noinfo
   @{"VERBOSE     " LINK "VERBOSE"}    -verbose
   @{"CLEAN       " LINK "CLEAN"}    -clean
   @{"LOGFILE     " LINK "LOGFILE"}    -logfile
   @{"REPERTOIRE= " LINK "DUMMY"}    given path
   @{"LOGNAME=    " LINK "LOGNAME"}    -logname <path:name>

   The only missing TOOLTYPE would be "REQUESTER", but this one is
   useless, as the ASL requester automatically appears if the
   "REPERTOIRE=" TOOLTYPE is not activated.

   Icons included with the program were designed by @{B}Roy Krister Ellingsen@{UB}
   a sympathetic Norway inhabitant, very happy since he could spare
   several Mb on his harddisk after having used twin :)
@ENDNODE

@NODE "LANGUAGE"

  Languages:

  Twin is localized and speaks fluently:

   * French  (built-in, cocorico)
   * English (catalog)
   * Swedish (catalog, courtesy Jonas Holmqvist)
   * German  (catalog, courtesy Arnold Schoenebeck)

  If somebody makes a translation in any other language, it would
  be kind to send me a copy via @{"email" LINK "ME"} so I could
  include it in the next distribution.

@ENDNODE

